The paper discusses a distributed storage architecture that exploits the capabilities of programmable switches to achieve near-linear scalability without sacrificing consistency. This involves detecting read-write conflicts in the network, which suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of Barefoot Tofino switches, which are commonly used in network infrastructure, suggesting that the paper may also belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category. The paper also discusses the integration of Harmonia with Redis, a popular open-source in-memory data structure store, which suggests that the paper may belong to the Operating Systems (cs.OS) sub-category. The paper also discusses replication protocols such as primary-backup, chain replication, Viewstamped Replication, and NOPaxos, which suggests that the paper may belong to the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the implementation of Harmonia on a cluster of commodity servers, which suggests that the paper may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category.
